events.body:
@hebasto Thanks for the review. I've updated the action to use the built-in `GITHUB_WORKSPACE` and removed the redundant variable. 

Regarding the injection hardening: while these contexts aren't directly user-controlled here, mapping them to environment variables is a more robust way to handle multiline inputs and prevents potential quote-mangling in the `bash -c` wrapping. 

@real-or-random Thanks for the ACK. Glad to see support for establishing safer patterns in the CI scripts.

@real-or-random Command injection from environment variables containing shell-sensitive characters like single quotes or newlines is what I'm primarily trying to block here. 

Someone who can influence an environment variable used in the workflowperhaps through a PR from a fork or a compromised upstream jobcould use a single quote to break out of the `run` script's wrapping. If I interpolate `${{ toJSON(env) }}` directly into a shell command, the runner might end up executing arbitrary code if the data is malformed.

Using a dedicated environment variable to hold the JSON blob and then reading it from a file keeps the data entirely out of the shell's command line. Moving the data into a file-based workflow ensures the script is robust against multiline or untrusted inputs, so I don't have to worry about the shell misinterpreting the data.
